{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17642462","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17642462"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:40:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:40:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17944"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17944","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17944"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.05,0.21,0.68,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10658"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78674"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10658","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10658"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17944"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64017"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7573"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24830"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24831"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78674","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78674"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following bones of the neurocranium is paired?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Occipital","Frontal","Ethmoid","Parietal","Sphenoid"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe neurocranium is the part of the skull that encloses the brain. It consists of both paired and unpaired bones. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eparietal\u003C/strong\u003E bones are paired, meaning there are two of them, one on each side of the skull. They form a large part of the sides and roof of the cranial cavity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eoccipital\u003C/strong\u003E bone is unpaired and forms the back and base of the skull.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Efrontal\u003C/strong\u003E bone is unpaired and forms the forehead and the upper part of the eye sockets.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eethmoid\u003C/strong\u003E bone is unpaired and contributes to the medial wall of the orbit, the nasal cavity, and the nasal septum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esphenoid\u003C/strong\u003E bone is unpaired and is located at the base of the skull, contributing to the floor of the cranial cavity and the sides of the skull.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The parietal bones are paired bones of the neurocranium.","The neurocranium consists of both paired and unpaired bones.","Understanding the anatomy of the skull is crucial for clinical practice, especially in neurosurgery."],"references":["Singh, V. (2023). Textbook of Anatomy-Head, Neck and Brain, Volume III-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Patestas, M. A., \u0026 Gartner, L. P. (2016). A textbook of neuroanatomy. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Patel, C. R., Fernandez-Miranda, J. C., Wang, W. H., \u0026 Wang, E. W. (2016). Skull Base Anatomy. Otolaryngologic clinics of North America, 49(1), 9\u201320. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.otc.2015.09.001","Anderson, B. W., Kortz, M. W., Black, A. C., \u0026 Al Kharazi, K. A. (2023). Anatomy, Head and Neck, Skull. In StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64017"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17944"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64017","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64017"},"at